description:
Issue 45 focuses on a recap of BotCon 2012. If you were at the show, a great review, and if you weren't, a very cool extended glimpse at what BotCon is all about! We also spotlight two more MTMTE profiles, Windbreaker and Flamefeather, showcase our final 2012 installment of the Allspark Almanac Addendum and in the current comic story "A Flash Forward", the master plan of the Cybertronian known as "Jhiaxus" is finally revealed!

Issue 48 of the TCC Magazine announces the BotCon 2013 Convention set theme. Though the Botcon theme is just the icing on the Issue 48 cake! Also in this issue we have a great sit down with Clint Chapman from the Transformers brand team where we talk about Transformers Prime: Beast Hunters, two all-new MTMTE profiles, an all-new Recordicons and the final installment to this year's club story "A Flash Forward". All this and more in Issue 48 of the TCC Magazine! Cover art by Robby Musso featuring the TFSS 1.0 character CIRCUIT.

description: After commanding the Titans in their war against the Olympians, Atlas was forced to hold up the heavens on his shoulders. His life was a tragic story of a lone God fighting boredom on Mount Olympus. However, monitoring the earth from above, Atlas watched Earth change and the emergence of super powered beings donning capes and tights. Growing restless and craving adventure, Atlas decides to take the world in his hands and become one of the Earth's newest heroes.

description: Back in 2009, the Infinetics Weapons Development Center was designing the next big thing in tactical weaponry…the Wildcard Tactical Mechanical. Equipped with the latest in protective armor and destructive ballistics, this mechanical upright also featured a highly controversial “on-demand” decision making program at the core of its operating system…the ability to make decisions without programmer entry or instruction. The Infinetics field test is a smashing success…right before it goes atrociously wrong. The definitive origin of Deadzone starts here in Deadzone #10, Hard Wear: 1.0.

Collects Alter Ego #1-4:

ALTER EGO, first published in 1986, is a super-hero comic that salutes the great super-heroes of the 1930s & 1940s -- the "Golden Age" of American comics.

description:
An anthology of stories from the first decade of American Splendor comics, 1976-1986.

  1. Introduction - (Crumb) Robert Crumb talks about Harvey Pekar's methods and vision
  2. The Harvey Pekar Name Story - (Pekar / Crumb) Harvey talks about his name.
  3. The Young Crumb Story - (Pekar / Crumb) Pekar tells a rambling story about meeting Crumb and getting started in comics.
  4. A Fantasy - (Pekar / Crumb) Pekar strongarms Crumb into doing more work for him.
  5. Ozzie Nelson's Open Letter to Crumb - (Pekar / Dumm) an open letter allegedly from Ozzie Nelson to R. Crumb.

volume.name: American Splendor: The Life and Times of Harvey Pekar

name: Humain

description: Paranoia, frustration, dreams, violence, jazz, inspiration, history, zydeco, muckraking, loneliness, sex, divorce, Hollywood, adoption, and Toby! All the elements of a classic, eclectic American novel, and they're packed into a comic book. Harvey Pekar returns with yet another chapter of autobiography, music history, and societal rants. Featuring art by a bevy of talented folks, and experiences from one tortured soul, this millennial issue of American Splendor promises to enrich, inform, and give you ample reason never to visit the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame. This very special issue also sports a photo cover of our man Harvey himself!

volume.name: American Splendor: Portrait of the Author in His Declining Years
